,once he left his body, Kali started in full flow. All Puranas were c=\r\nomposed after this, hence these are scriptures of the Kali-Yuga, as are Tan=\r\ntras]\n\n3. These 10/9 Avataras have a fixed sequence of appearance. Matysa, =\r\nKurma, Varaha, Narasimha, Vamana, Parashurama, Rama, Krshna, (Buddha) and K=\r\nalki. There is an unmistakeable connection of the form and sequence of thes=\r\ne main avatars with the evolution of life on earth. From the aquatic, to th=\r\ne amphibian, to the land-animal, to the half-animal-half-man, to the dwarf =\r\nman (first human life form who immediately takes possession of this earth r=\r\nepresented by Vamana&#39;s 3 steps), to the Rajashik avatara of Parashurama mov=\r\ning around with an axe, to the Sattwa Guna Avatara of Rama, to the Nirguna =\r\nAvatara of Krshna. Also, this indicates that spirituality is not to be sepa=\r\nrated into another world, but is a progressive realization of the various m=\r\nanifestation and potentials that lie inherent in the consciousness and its =\r\ndevelopment through various life-forms. Larger spirituality of earth and ev=\r\nolution go hand in hand. That is Nature&#39;s grand design for life on earth.\n\n=\r\n4. In this specifc context, I am only focusing on the parable of these main=\r\n 9/10 Avatars. It is not my contention that if one worships say Matysa Avat=\r\nara, one will not attain to a state of liberation of the soul. As is the na=\r\nture of spiritual cosmology in Hinduism, any Devata can lead a person to an=\r\ny depth of realization. And each one of the Avatars of Vishnu are self-real=\r\nized in their own way and can be consider super-massive spiritual dynamos.\n=\r\n\n\n=C2=A05. Of these, naturally, Rama and Krshna are most adored because the=\r\ny represent a stage of evolution, both inside as well as outside, which soc=\r\niety can relate of much easier, in this age. Rama represents, for me, the s=\r\ntage of most satwic mind. A satwic mind is in control of itself. It known h=\r\now to transform the animal tendencies within and without - monkeys - into a=\r\n constructive force for a greater purpose. However, as with a state of full=\r\n Sattwa Guna, there can be instances, even though few, of dejection. For it=\r\n is static in nature and will change only when circumstances force it to. A=\r\ns per the Valmiki Ramayana, Rama did feel dejected while searching for Sita=\r\n in the forest. He did have a moments fear before the final assault on Rava=\r\nna, which was dispelled by Agsatha when the later revealed the stotra of th=\r\ne Sun to Rama. At the end of the final battle, Rama tells Sita, in a most d=\r\nispassionate manner, that he killed Ravana not to rescue her, but it was\n t=\r\nhe Dharma to do so, and to unhold his family honour. That too was the dharm=\r\na of that age when he lived, family honor. The way I look at this grand epi=\r\nc, and I bow humbly to the genius of Rishis Valmiki for representing the th=\r\nings as they are, as a scribe, as a poet, as an observer, and not adding hi=\r\ns own preferences to it anywhere, in the 14 years of tribulation that Rama =\r\nfaced which culminated into his killing Ravana, he changed into the most di=\r\nspassionate leader, such that no personal consideration or emotions or pass=\r\nions can overturn the Rajadharma. His life is a lesson of what a true leade=\r\nr must be!\n\nKrshna, OTOH, had this immaculate detachment right from birth. =\r\nI am not taking his=C2=A0 supernatural feats into account. It is his singul=\r\nar and constant detachment from situations, from people, from environment, =\r\nfrom circumstances that mark his life. At the age of eight, he decides to l=\r\neave Vrindavana for Mathura. All his friends, his foster parents, his villa=\r\nge-folks who so loved him, pleaded with him that it would make no sense for=\r\n him to leave the shelter, love and comfort of his happy, settled village l=\r\nife and head into an unknown destiny and destination. Krshna tried to reaso=\r\nn with them, then he understood that they won&#39;t understand, he promised he =\r\nwill return back once his work in Mathura is over. He never returned. Later=\r\n, much later, when the Gopis came to him asking him to participate in their=\r\n dance, he obliged. But the moment some of them started getting jealous and=\r\n possessive of Krshna, he removed himself quietly from the scene, saying th=\r\nat he\n belongs to everyone equally and no one has any special right over hi=\r\nm. When Shishupala abused Krshna, the later merely kept dropping flowers on=\r\n the floor, smiling and counting. The moment the 100th abuse was over, he s=\r\nwiftly cut off Shishupala&#39;s head and was back into his poise. But when Bhur=\r\nishrava unfairly accused Krshna of being a revolutionist and charlatan, Krs=\r\nhna did not kill him. When Duryodhana, who used to think of Krshna as anoth=\r\ner black magician, wanted to arrest him, Krshna showed his vikarala roopa i=\r\nn the assembly of kings, yet he did not finish the enemies off. The very ne=\r\nxt moment he was back into his own poised self. Never in the whole Mahabhar=\r\nata is there one instance of his going overboard, never a single shade of d=\r\nepression, equivocation, or lack of confidence in his actions, irrespective=\r\n of what others say or think of him. And then right in the middle of the gr=\r\neatest war he had the perfect equipoise to deliver the most sublime\n spirit=\r\nual philosophy. That is why his life remains the best ideal of Karma-Yoga. =\r\nFor a true Karma-Yogi by definition can never be dejected. It is impossible=\r\n. Neither the action nor the results belong to the instrument. When running=\r\n away from the battle-field and killing Kaliya Yavana, or when advising Bhe=\r\nema to tear apart Jarashanda, or gesturing Bheema to hit Duryodhana below t=\r\nhe waist, or getting Shikhandi to face Bhisma, Krshna, as if by some Divine=\r\n Intuition, knew exactly how the situations must be lined up which would ca=\r\nuse the destruction of these people. This kind of knowledge cannot come by =\r\nthe rational thinking. But happens when one is constantly and consciously c=\r\nonnected to the Universal Force. We do not find these kind of complex situa=\r\ntions in the Rama Avatara, at least in the Valmiki Ramayana. Of course, if =\r\nwe take the Adhbut Ramayana or such other auxilliary texts and retelling, w=\r\ne get a different picture. In the Adbhuta Ramayana we have a\n 1000 headed d=\r\nemon attacking Rama after he kills Ravana, and then Sita turns into Adya Sh=\r\nakti and demolishes the 1000 headed demon and Rama worships her. But if we =\r\ntake only the Ramayana and the Mahabharata, the picture that emerges is ver=\r\ny clear. Rama is the embodiment of Sattwic mind. Therefore he displays all =\r\nthe great characteristics of satwa, chief of which is self-control, as well=\r\n as the occasional sadness caused due to separation from his wife Sita whom=\r\n, at least until Ravana was destroyed, he loved very dearly. Satwa guna cre=\r\nates a true saint, but can also cause some grief when the stability is shak=\r\nen. Krshna was gunatita. He had no attachment to anything in this world - m=\r\nan, women, deva, danava, friend, enemy - and therefore he was never affecte=\r\nd any trace of negative emotion. His Ananda never left him even in the most=\r\n trying situations.\n\n6. Buddha was great spiritual force in this world. But=\r\n I do not see him fit in the scheme of evolutionary Avatars. His realizatio=\r\nn, the one he advocated, is a static realization, an end in a void. This is=\r\n clearly denying of the reality of this earth. I find this not in tune with=\r\n what either Rama or Krshna espoused. None of them negated this world. If n=\r\negation of this world and life is the final aim, then why send so many avat=\r\nars at crucial stages of evolutionary development? If the spiritual impact =\r\non masses is the reason for Buddha being an Avatara, then why not Jesus or =\r\nZorathrusta.? They are no less impactful in that sense. But do they fit in =\r\nthe scheme of spiritual line that these 9 Avataras of Narayana indicate in =\r\na most logical manner? No. As such many vaishnava traditions in parts of In=\r\ndia, do not consider Buddha to be an avatara. Realization, to be complete a=\r\nnd holistic, must be both static and dynamic, outside of life as well as in=\r\nside of life.\n That is why the Tantras formed their own kind of spiritual p=\r\nhilosophy, of the world as body of Shakti and therefore an object of revere=\r\nnce and realization.\n\n7. The original literature of the Nath Yogis used to =\r\nmention 9 chakras. These are centers of psychological functions. 6 inside t=\r\nhe human body and 3 too subtle, or non-developed in most people, even seeke=\r\nrs. It is my belief that each of the 9 Avataras - excluding Buddha - corres=\r\npond to the full power and force of one of these 9 Chakras. Similarly, the =\r\n9 grahas, or that which can modify consciousness or allow the consciousness=\r\n to explore and express itself is various possiblities, are 9 in number. Th=\r\ne lagna is a reference point and not a graha. Therefore the chief Avatars w=\r\nho represent the parable of evolution are nine in number. And the ninth of =\r\nthe sequence is yet to come.\n\n8. I cannot comment on which graha would typi=\r\ncally represent which Avatara. I know of what the BPHS says, however, it is=\r\n my belief - feel free to disagree with it -:)[one cannot rule out some dee=\r\np-rooted corruption of understanding or textual misrepresentation in this K=\r\nali-Yuga] - that the Atmah among the Avataras has not yet appeared. It will=\r\n be Kalki, or as Vimalananda seems to say in the Aghora books, Nishkalanka =\r\n- the stainless one. There is only one thing which is perfectly stainless, =\r\nthe Atmah .After a Nirguna/Gunatita awastha comes living in the full and co=\r\nmplete purity and might and force and strength of the Atmah. By the sheer d=\r\nint of his purity the last Avatara will burn away opposing forces of this w=\r\norld and fulfill the purpose of evolution. Even Krshna used diplomacy at va=\r\nrious points in his adult life to achieve his ends. Kalki, I am speculating=\r\n, won&#39;t even need that. The white horse and that sword is a metaphor. He wi=\r\nll be the only one\n capable enough to rectify the various errors and corrup=\r\ntions that beset our age. \n\nWell, this is how I look at the story of Avatar=\r\nas. It is perfectly ok not to agree with my views, but I am reasonably sang=\r\nuine now that this is what is closer to truth.\n\n-Regards\n=C2=A0Rajarshi\n\n\na=\r\nwaktam wyaktimApannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah |\nparam bhAwamajAnanto mamAwya=\r\nyamanuttamam ||[7:24]\n\n\n________________________________\n From: Narasimha P=\r\n.V.R. Rao &lt;pvr108@...&gt;\nTo: Vedic Wisdom &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com=\r\n&gt; \nSent: Thursday, 25 April 2013 9:00 AM\nSubject: [vedic-wisdom] Comparing =\r\nDasavataras!\n \n\n\n=C2=A0 \nNamaste friends,\n=C2=A0\nThere was a discussion on =\r\nLord Vishnu&#39;s Dasavataras on a limited access forum on Facebook. A learned =\r\nfriend wrote that &quot;Krshna is the God-man&quot;, &quot;Previous Avatars are a build-up=\r\n to this stage&quot; and &quot;Buddha after Krshna is like going back from the linear=\r\n progression of spirituality that the Avatars manifest one after the other =\r\nupto Krshna&quot;.\n=C2=A0\nI want to emphatically disagree with this notion that =\r\nDasavatars of a &quot;linear progression of spirituality..upto Krshna&quot;.\n=C2=A0\n*=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nEach avatara represents an aspect of Supreme in a per=\r\nfected form.\n=C2=A0\nMaharshi Parasara equated dasavataras with planets. For=\r\n example, Rama, Krishna and Narasimha are Sun, Moon and Mars, respectively.=\r\n\n=C2=A0\nWe also\n know that Sun, Moon, Mars, Mercury, Jupiter, Venus, Saturn=\r\n, Rahu and Ketu are personifications of soul, mind, energy/initiative/drive=\r\n, learning spirit, wisdom/discrimination, spirit of enjoyment/being happy, =\r\npatience/discipline, spirit of innovation/breaking barriers and detachment =\r\n(respectively).\n=C2=A0\nCorrespondingly, each avatara is an expression of th=\r\nat aspect of Supreme in a perfected form. Each story is an example of how t=\r\nhat aspect operates.\n=C2=A0\nLord Rama&#39;s story is a perfected example of how=\r\n soul operates. Lord Krishna&#39;s story is a perfected example of how mind ope=\r\nrates. Lord Vamana&#39;s story is a perfected example of how wisdom/discriminat=\r\nion operates. Lord Narasimha&#39;s story is a perfected example of how energy/d=\r\nrive/initiative operates.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nNow, let us rememb=\r\ner one basic thing. Soul in us, mind in us, energy in us,\n learning spirit =\r\nin us, wisdom in us, happiness in us, discipline/patience in us - all these=\r\n are different manifestations of the same Self. However, when Self manifest=\r\ns as these different aspects, it has different qualities and plays differen=\r\nt roles. There is no comparison between them.\n=C2=A0\nWe MAY focus on one as=\r\npect of us first, perfect it and then perfect other aspects through it. But=\r\n, we need balance between all aspects in the end. Similarly, these differen=\r\nt aspects of Supreme Being are incomparable and are in a balance working to=\r\ngether in the Cosmos.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nOne who is fascinated b=\r\ny the qualities of soul may like the story that demonstrates how soul opera=\r\ntes; one who is fascinated by the qualities of mind may like the story that=\r\n demonstrates how mind operates, and one who is fascinated by the qualities=\r\n of wisdom may like the story that\n demonstrates how wisdom operates. And s=\r\no on. But this is just a matter of taste and subjective preference.\n=C2=A0\n=\r\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nLet us focus on Rama and Krishna, i.e. soul and mind.=\r\n Soul is seen as a representative of god in us, because of some basic attri=\r\nbutes of it. It is the higher self and has no agendas, no likes or dislikes=\r\n.\n=C2=A0\nOnce mind fancies a separate existence with some agendas/desires, =\r\nsoul supports the individualized consciousness stemming from that fancy and=\r\n sees it as its dharma. It lends strength and support to EVERY aspect of th=\r\nis individualized consciousness (e.g. mind, energy, intellect, learning abi=\r\nlity, enjoyment, discipline etc). It supports them fully and yet has no des=\r\nires/agendas/likes/dislikes of its own! It impassionately witnesses and rec=\r\nords all of one&#39;s agendas and karmas so that Laws of Nature give proper fru=\r\nits later\n on. It does all that despite full awareness that it is neither d=\r\noing those karmas nor receiving the fruits. As mind and other aspects of th=\r\ne individualized consciousness entertain the notion that they are doing thi=\r\nngs and begetting the fruits, soul supports them fully in this play. It see=\r\ns that as its dharma and does it impassionately.\n=C2=A0\nNow, does this soun=\r\nd exciting? Perhaps not to all. This functionality of an impassionate witne=\r\nss supporting the play, may not seem interesting enough to some.\n=C2=A0\nOn =\r\nthe other hand, mind has likes, dislikes and agendas. It is constantly purs=\r\nuing those agendas, getting things and achieving things. Movement of mind i=\r\ns what keeps the individualization going!!! Though soul is the support for =\r\neverything else in the individualized consciousness, soul is a witness doin=\r\ng its dharma impassionately. It is mind that keeps the individualization go=\r\ning and brings in agendas and passion and even decides/affects\n every entit=\r\ny&#39;s dharma. That way, mind is really the &quot;boss&quot; of the individualization. N=\r\no wonder Krishna&#39;s life appeals more to one who may be excited by this desc=\r\nription!\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nLord Krishna is obviously awe-inspi=\r\nring, but let me put Rama&#39;s life in perspective.\n=C2=A0\nRama&#39;s life demonst=\r\nrates how soul operates. At a young age, he received Brahma Jnana from Vasi=\r\nshtha and became realized. Yet, he did whatever was his &quot;dharma&quot;. He helped=\r\n Vishwamitra. Soon after marriage, he was given kingdom. At the last moment=\r\n, his father banished him to forest at the behest of his step-mother and hi=\r\ns step-brother was given the throne. He had no complaints. Though his fathe=\r\nr, step-mother and step-brother felt guilty to various degrees, he himself =\r\nsupported and consoled all three and followed his dharma impassionately. Th=\r\nough he knew leaving Sita in the forest\n with Lakshmana and going after the=\r\n golden deer would cause problems, he did it impassionately when Sita insis=\r\nted. When she was kidnapped by Ravana, he searched for her and fought the b=\r\nattle. He never faulted Sita for forcing him to leave her or faulted Lakshm=\r\nana for leaving her later. He accepted every life situation with no complai=\r\nnts and did the best possible action then. Even as he killed Ravana, he did=\r\n so without hatred or anger, but as his impassionate dharma. Even as Ravana=\r\n was dying, he went to him and respectfully learned some subjects that were=\r\n going to disappear with Ravana!\n=C2=A0\nRama is a perfect example of a libe=\r\nrated man with no desires or agendas who impassionately discharges one&#39;s dh=\r\narma arising from the momentum of karmas before liberation. THAT is basical=\r\nly what soul does!\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nAs another example, let us=\r\n look at Lord\n Vaamana. His story is a perfect demonstration of how wisdom/=\r\ndiscrimination operates.\n=C2=A0\nHe was born as a learned pygmy. He filled t=\r\nhe entire cosmos to rid earth of a charitable demon king with many great qu=\r\nalities.\n=C2=A0\nWisdom/discrimination makes one humble and unassuming. When=\r\n one is doing good work but tainted with demonic qualities (e.g. pride or a=\r\nttachment), one&#39;s discrimination is not pleased until that pride is suppres=\r\nsed. When wisdom fills one&#39;s entire consciousness, then demonic qualities a=\r\nre completely suppressed.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nPlease think about=\r\n the other avataras. The stories can be understood as perfect demonstration=\r\ns of how various aspects of our consciousness operate, based on clues from =\r\nMaharshi Parasara.\n=C2=A0\nLet us not compare Dasavataras, but celebrate eac=\r\nh of them separately. Of course, if you are more\n attracted to one of them,=\r\n please think about that avatara more and develop devotion. They are ALL ca=\r\npable of relieving us from samsara.\n=C2=A0\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n=C2=A0\nBy the wa=\r\ny, happy Hanumajjayanti to those who celebrate it today (there are differen=\r\nt schools of thought).\n=C2=A0\nBest regards,\nNarasimha\n--------\nAstrology & =\r\nSpirituality Resources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org \n--------\n\n\n \r\n---2020808392-1609910660-1367667282=:39346\r\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=utf-8\r\nContent-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable\r\n\r\n&lt;html&gt;&lt;body&gt;&lt;div style=3D&quot;color:#000; background-color:#fff; font-family:Co=\r\nurier New, courier, monaco, monospace, sans-serif;font-size:12pt&quot;&gt;&lt;div&gt;&